00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:05.260
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D. C.

00:00:20.230 --> 00:00:23.250
&gt;&gt; Hirad Dinavari: On behalf of
the library, I quickly wanted

00:00:23.250 --> 00:00:26.090
to take a minute to
give my condolences

00:00:26.090 --> 00:00:30.520
to all the Iranian women,
Persian-speaking audiences

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:33.810
in Afghanistan, Tajikistan
and elsewhere for the passing

00:00:33.810 --> 00:00:36.410
of the poetess Simin Behbahani.

00:00:36.410 --> 00:00:40.410
It is with a heavy heart that
I say this in the exhibition.

00:00:40.410 --> 00:00:45.430
We have selected a whole section
on women who do Persian Poetry

00:00:45.430 --> 00:00:49.970
and Persian language works from
Iran, Afghanistan and Tajikistan.

00:00:49.970 --> 00:00:53.860
Simin is one of the
most important poetesses

00:00:53.860 --> 00:00:56.770
of the current time,
the Lioness of Iran.

00:00:56.770 --> 00:00:59.650
And known as the national
poet of Iran.

00:00:59.650 --> 00:01:01.570
Dr. Billington and maybe Jane

00:01:01.570 --> 00:01:04.710
when they visited Iran
in 2004 met with her.

00:01:04.710 --> 00:01:07.070
She was gracious enough
to give her time.

00:01:07.070 --> 00:01:12.400
And it is a matter of great
sadness to us all to see her pass.

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:16.950
And with that I'm going to pass
the grand to Dr. Fatemeh Keshavarz

00:01:16.950 --> 00:01:20.530
and ask her to introduce
our lovely speaker.

00:01:20.530 --> 00:01:21.830
Thank you very much.

00:01:21.830 --> 00:01:24.340
There you go.

00:01:24.340 --> 00:01:27.080
&gt;&gt; Fatemeh Keshavarz:
Farzaneh and I go way back.

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:34.110
There has been no particularly
important turning point in my life

00:01:34.110 --> 00:01:38.540
in which he hasn't been involved,
whether it was being out for tenure

00:01:38.540 --> 00:01:42.200
or getting promoted or you know,

00:01:42.200 --> 00:01:44.730
going from institution
to institution.

00:01:44.730 --> 00:01:50.300
To actually reading each other's
work and also reading my manuscript

00:01:50.300 --> 00:01:55.060
and always being a wonderful
reader and supporter.

00:01:55.060 --> 00:02:00.290
So it is with special
pleasure that I introduce.

00:02:00.290 --> 00:02:05.770 position:56%
Farzaneh did a Ph. D in
comparative literature in University

00:02:05.770 --> 00:02:08.540
of California, UCLA,
and I believe she worked

00:02:08.540 --> 00:02:10.410 position:56%
with Amin Benoni [spelling assumed].

00:02:10.410 --> 00:02:11.960
I also know she worked closely

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:16.020
with many other scholars including
Ishmat Moyedin [spelling assumed]

00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:17.320
and others.

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:19.970
But I believe that Amin
Benoni was crucial.

00:02:19.970 --> 00:02:24.300
And we do indeed miss him.

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:27.400
He's been a really important voice

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:32.650
in criticism and particularly
poetry.

00:02:32.650 --> 00:02:38.820
And in her thesis, Fazaneh
worked on Forough Farrokhzhad

00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:40.760
from the feminist perspective.

00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:43.730
So this has been a topic
that's been very close

00:02:43.730 --> 00:02:46.890
to her heart for a very long time.

00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:53.630
She's written close to 100
if not more I'm sure articles

00:02:53.630 --> 00:03:00.460
and book chapters and op-eds and
just contributions that just range

00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:04.280
from highly specialized
and scholarly to things

00:03:04.280 --> 00:03:07.930
that would appear in New York
Times or Washington Post.

00:03:07.930 --> 00:03:11.170
And do that very important
job of reaching

00:03:11.170 --> 00:03:17.660
out to the broader
interested public.

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:22.850
Her first book, her first
major book actually in English,

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:25.870
Veils and Words is a classic.

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:34.520
It's about wars that
women poets and writers,

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:39.300
their journey within the Persian
culture and you know from 17, 18,

00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:43.350
19th century to the present time.

00:03:43.350 --> 00:03:49.860
And her latest book, which I
believe came out in 2011, yes,

00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:55.970
Words Not Swords, takes that
another step forward on what it is

00:03:55.970 --> 00:03:59.640
that women and women's
literature, and looking at it

00:03:59.640 --> 00:04:05.670 position:56%
from a gendered lens does to
understand the role of these voices,

00:04:05.670 --> 00:04:09.710
rather than considering
them silent or censored.

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:12.830
So that has been a
tremendous contribution.

00:04:12.830 --> 00:04:16.370
I believe you're working
on a biography of Forough,

00:04:16.370 --> 00:04:20.870
so we are eagerly looking
forward to that and with

00:04:20.870 --> 00:04:24.410
that I'm just going
to invite Fazaneh.

00:04:24.410 --> 00:04:29.510
Please join me in giving
her a very warm welcome.

00:04:29.510 --> 00:04:32.040
[ Applause ]

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:33.950
Farzanah Milani: Thank you for
