00:37:57.290 --> 00:38:05.300 position:56%
Because although some people loved
the poem, there were a lot of people

00:38:05.300 --> 00:38:12.160
who were totally shocked
and aggravated by this poem.

00:38:12.160 --> 00:38:16.330
Love poems, adulterous
relationships,

00:38:16.330 --> 00:38:21.200
are a dime a dozen in
Persian literature.

00:38:21.200 --> 00:38:26.830
We have plenty of adulterous
women in Persian literature.

00:38:26.830 --> 00:38:34.550
So what was it about this
poem that became so scandalous

00:38:34.550 --> 00:38:39.660
that brought Forough immediately
to a level of notoriety,

00:38:39.660 --> 00:38:45.180
of scandal that was
unheard of before her?

00:38:46.340 --> 00:38:52.000
What was in this poem that
shocked and titillated the readers?

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:58.740
Because it really did
titillate a lot of people too.

00:38:58.740 --> 00:39:05.600
I have a few suggestions and
I'm sure there are plenty more.

00:39:09.150 --> 00:39:13.150
This woman calls herself a sinner.

00:39:13.150 --> 00:39:16.720
The poem is called Sin
and she begins with I,

00:39:16.720 --> 00:39:18.550
which his very unusual,

00:39:18.550 --> 00:39:22.540
an autobiographical
statement for a woman.

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:26.140
In a culture where
autobiographical statements

00:39:26.140 --> 00:39:29.310
and life narratives
are not quite allowed.

00:39:29.310 --> 00:39:30.770
At least they were not allowed.

00:39:30.770 --> 00:39:33.540
Now everybody is writing a memoir.

00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:35.130
And my aunt too.

00:39:35.130 --> 00:39:37.750
But back then it wasn't like that.

00:39:37.750 --> 00:39:42.730
We didn't have biographies
or autobiographies by women.

00:39:42.730 --> 00:39:45.480
So the poem starts with I.

00:39:45.480 --> 00:39:48.690
"I sinned."

00:39:48.690 --> 00:39:54.890
But more importantly, she has
sinned but she is not repentful.

00:39:54.890 --> 00:39:59.360
In fact, throughout the poem
she is quite exhilarated.

00:39:59.360 --> 00:40:02.220
Something mysterious
has happened to her.

00:40:02.220 --> 00:40:07.580
The poem is about the awakening
of a woman to sexuality,

00:40:07.580 --> 00:40:11.040
to the joy of physical union.

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:15.020
She has never experienced it
before and she has at this time

00:40:15.020 --> 00:40:18.160
and she's writing about it.

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:23.500
So she's talking about it [Foreign
name], but she's also talking

00:40:23.500 --> 00:40:26.660
about freedom of expression.

00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:28.030
"I committed a sin.

00:40:28.030 --> 00:40:30.740
Yes, it is a sin.

00:40:30.740 --> 00:40:32.630
But eat your heart out.

00:40:32.630 --> 00:40:34.600
I am not repentful.

00:40:34.600 --> 00:40:39.140
And I'm going to tell
you all about it."

00:40:40.210 --> 00:40:44.990
More importantly, this
adulterous woman, unlike the slew

00:40:44.990 --> 00:40:48.410
of adulterous women
in Persian literature,

00:40:48.410 --> 00:40:57.640
does not undergo a
religious awakening.

00:40:59.620 --> 00:41:04.690
