00:43:22.760 --> 00:43:30.270
In fact she did use
pseudonyms, pen names,

00:43:30.270 --> 00:43:33.520 position:56%
later for some of her prose writing.

00:43:33.520 --> 00:43:37.680
Two very interesting pen names.

00:43:37.680 --> 00:43:43.320
[Foreign name], the Iconoclast, and
[Foreign name], Born of Fairies.

00:43:43.320 --> 00:43:44.620
That I know of.

00:43:44.620 --> 00:43:49.280
There might be others that
I'm not still aware of.

00:43:53.090 --> 00:44:00.180
Forough found herself at the
eye of the gathering storm.

00:44:00.180 --> 00:44:03.290
The father, Mr. Farrakhzhad,

00:44:03.290 --> 00:44:06.980
was furious with the
publication of this Sin.

00:44:06.980 --> 00:44:11.670
And of course the husband
was as well.

00:44:11.670 --> 00:44:20.320
I have heard that when this poem
was published, and I don't say

00:44:20.320 --> 00:44:23.670
that with joy -- my
heart goes to him --

00:44:23.670 --> 00:44:26.380
Mr. Shapour, Parviz
Shapour the husband,

00:44:26.380 --> 00:44:29.510 position:56%
did not leave home for a whole week.

00:44:29.510 --> 00:44:33.960
He just could not face the world.

00:44:33.960 --> 00:44:37.890
And you understand, in a
culture where the honor

00:44:37.890 --> 00:44:44.540
of a man depends on
sexual acts of women.

00:44:44.540 --> 00:44:48.880
And to me that's the prison, but
that is nonetheless how it is,

00:44:48.880 --> 00:44:53.550
how it was back then and how it
is to a certain extent today.

00:44:53.550 --> 00:44:56.220
This is Nasir Quidiar
[spelling assumed].

00:44:56.220 --> 00:45:01.820
Not much usually is known about
him, which is interesting.

00:45:01.820 --> 00:45:06.840
I will tell you, he is the man
for whom Sin was published.

00:45:06.840 --> 00:45:10.030
He is the beloved of Sin.

00:45:10.030 --> 00:45:16.000
And I'm not intruding
upon Forough's privacy.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:18.220
In a minute you will see that.

00:45:18.220 --> 00:45:26.160
At the time in the '50's it
became the talk of town in Tehran.

00:45:26.160 --> 00:45:30.580
It's often mentioned that Forough
Farrokhzhad published her first

00:45:30.580 --> 00:45:35.350
poetry collection when she was 17.

00:45:35.350 --> 00:45:41.490
I have not come across any such
poems or poetry collection.

00:45:41.490 --> 00:45:47.270
Her first collection
is called Captive.

00:45:47.270 --> 00:45:54.670
And it was published in 1955.

00:45:55.720 --> 00:46:02.120
Most of the poems in it are in
fact written in 1953 and 1954.

00:46:02.120 --> 00:46:06.110
So I don't know how she could have
published Asir when she was 17.

00:46:06.110 --> 00:46:09.640 position:56%
So I think that's a false statement.

00:46:16.050 --> 00:46:19.720
Asir was by itself a novelty.

00:46:19.720 --> 00:46:24.560
For the first time in
Iranian literary history,

00:46:24.560 --> 00:46:30.780
a woman from a non-literary
family was publishing a collection

00:46:30.780 --> 00:46:32.930
of poems.

00:46:32.930 --> 00:46:38.460
Prior to her, none of the poems,
none of the poetry collections

00:46:38.460 --> 00:46:44.280
by our women writers have
been published by people

00:46:44.280 --> 00:46:47.860
who were not in literary families.

00:46:47.860 --> 00:46:51.390
[Foreign names] and the
list goes on and on.

00:46:51.390 --> 00:47:01.940
Significantly, the poem Sin
which brought Forough to fame

00:47:01.940 --> 00:47:08.900 position:56%
and notoriety was excised from Asir.

00:47:13.160 --> 00:47:17.880
And apparently the relationship
with Quidiar had gone sour.

00:47:17.880 --> 00:47:24.710
So soon Asir became a
highly acclaimed poem

00:47:24.710 --> 00:47:27.370
because it was unusual poetry.

00:47:27.370 --> 00:47:29.770
It had 44 poems.

00:47:29.770 --> 00:47:34.440
And it had an introduction
by Mr. Chafa.

00:47:34.440 --> 00:47:38.830
So I asked Mr. Chafa.

00:47:38.830 --> 00:47:47.580
I said, "How did you end up
writing this introduction to Asir?"

00:47:47.580 --> 00:47:54.640
Again, the story is so important if
you want to put it in the context

00:47:54.640 --> 00:47:59.420
of the difficulties women
confronted in becoming writers

00:47:59.420 --> 00:48:02.150
or poets in Iran of the time.

00:48:02.150 --> 00:48:08.770
So apparently the publisher
had told Forough that in order

00:48:08.770 --> 00:48:13.670
for her poetry collection to be
published, they would want her

00:48:13.670 --> 00:48:21.550
to have a major writer write an
introduction to the collection.

00:48:21.550 --> 00:48:28.290
So one afternoon, as Mr. Chafa told
me, there was a knock at the door.

00:48:28.290 --> 00:48:34.560
He goes to open the door and
there is a young woman there

00:48:34.560 --> 00:48:37.970
with a book in her hand.

00:48:37.970 --> 00:48:46.840
And she introduces herself and Mr.
Chafa immediately recognizes him

00:48:46.840 --> 00:48:51.140 position:56%
because at the time many people,
definitely people in literature knew

00:48:51.140 --> 00:48:54.690
of Forough Farrokhzhad,
the poet of Sin.

00:48:54.690 --> 00:48:58.680
And she was invited in.

00:48:58.680 --> 00:49:03.090
And she tells him, "I'm
here because I want you

00:49:03.090 --> 00:49:06.600 position:56%
to write an introduction to my book.

00:49:06.600 --> 00:49:10.350
And that's the reason the
publisher wants you to do that.

00:49:10.350 --> 00:49:12.420
Would you consider doing it?"

00:49:12.420 --> 00:49:14.800
And Chafa says, "Of
course I will do it."

00:49:14.800 --> 00:49:18.880
So that's how Chafa
wrote the introduction.

00:49:18.880 --> 00:49:29.120
So Asir was published without
Sin, but significantly also

00:49:29.120 --> 00:49:33.670
without an afterword that
Forough had written to it.

00:49:33.670 --> 00:49:38.950
And that afterword, if you have not
read it, may I suggest you read it.

00:49:38.950 --> 00:49:41.000
It's called Tozi.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:44.190
It is really a manifesto
for Forough Farrokhzhad.

00:49:44.190 --> 00:49:46.360
I don't know why it was excised

00:49:46.360 --> 00:49:50.840
and I don't know why it's
not reprinted anywhere.

00:49:50.840 --> 00:49:53.150
I will be happy to
send you a copy of it

00:49:53.150 --> 00:49:54.990
if anybody is interested in it.

00:49:54.990 --> 00:50:00.450
I think we should all read what
a barely 20-year-old woman wrote

00:50:00.450 --> 00:50:07.370
about poetry and about women's
lives in Iran at the time.

00:50:07.370 --> 00:50:15.270
In Asir and then later in the
[Foreign name], Walls, Rebellion

00:50:15.270 --> 00:50:20.090
and Reborn, the other
four collections,

00:50:20.090 --> 00:50:21.490
these are the four collections

00:50:21.490 --> 00:50:24.260
that Forough published
during her lifetime.

00:50:24.260 --> 00:50:28.670
There are a few central themes
that are central to her life.

00:50:28.670 --> 00:50:32.850
So I'm going to quickly
try to just enumerate them.

00:50:32.850 --> 00:50:37.530
First of course is motherhood.

00:50:37.530 --> 00:50:43.480
Farrokhzhad was a teenage
mother and in the letters

00:50:43.480 --> 00:50:48.080
that you will see published
in the biography

00:50:48.080 --> 00:50:51.120
that hopefully will
be published soon,

00:50:51.120 --> 00:50:57.010
the pain of being separated
from her son.

00:50:57.010 --> 00:51:02.130
And the love that she had for
her son is really central,

00:51:02.130 --> 00:51:05.140
not only to her poetry but also

00:51:05.140 --> 00:51:08.150
to all the letters, to
many of the letters.

00:51:08.150 --> 00:51:14.880
And in fact, because she
chose poetry as a vocation,

00:51:14.880 --> 00:51:21.660
as a profession, she was
denied her right of motherhood.

00:51:21.660 --> 00:51:28.760
Fatherhood in Iran is a grant,
is a granted phenomenon.

00:51:28.760 --> 00:51:36.960 position:56%
All you have to do is to contribute
physically to the act of conception.

00:51:36.960 --> 00:51:42.630
A mother becomes a mother
with birth of the child,

00:51:42.630 --> 00:51:47.780
but to remain a mother
she has to earn that.

00:51:47.780 --> 00:51:51.780
Motherhood is not a
right for Iranian women.

00:51:51.780 --> 00:51:54.360
Motherhood is a privilege.

00:51:54.360 --> 00:51:59.200
And because Forough
Farrokhzhad divorced her husband

00:51:59.200 --> 00:52:06.040
and because she chose to be, as she
called it, she constantly said it

00:52:06.040 --> 00:52:11.030
in the letters, in the poems,
"I want to become a great poet."

00:52:11.030 --> 00:52:14.700
She said that since she was 19.

00:52:14.700 --> 00:52:16.540
"I want to become a great poet.

00:52:16.540 --> 00:52:19.370
And I can't reconcile
that with a life

00:52:19.370 --> 00:52:22.180
of domesticity and
raising children."

00:52:22.180 --> 00:52:24.790
But that didn't mean
that she didn't want

00:52:24.790 --> 00:52:29.820
to have her instinct
as a mother denied.

00:52:29.820 --> 00:52:36.040
So that caused her great
pain as many of you know.

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:47.830 position:56%
After Mr. Quidiar decided to publish
the detail of his relationship

00:52:47.830 --> 00:52:51.820
with Farrokhzhad in a serial
called [Foreign name],

00:52:51.820 --> 00:52:57.180
she was considered a
promiscuous woman now,

00:52:57.180 --> 00:53:02.940
not only by her own admission but
also by the admission of the lover.

00:53:02.940 --> 00:53:12.240 position:56%
And not only she was divorced, she
was denied custody rights of her son

00:53:12.240 --> 00:53:15.660
and eventually visitation
rights with her son.

00:53:15.660 --> 00:53:20.260
That pain remained with her
for the rest of her life.

00:53:23.440 --> 00:53:27.960 position:56%
It's interesting to note that before
the Feminine Mystique was published

00:53:27.960 --> 00:53:32.940
in the US and before Of Women
Born of [inaudible] was published

00:53:32.940 --> 00:53:35.930
in the US, Forough
Farrokhzhad had talked

00:53:35.930 --> 00:53:39.750
about both those issues
in her poetry.

00:53:39.750 --> 00:53:43.350
In particular her first
two poetry collections

00:53:43.350 --> 00:53:48.010
which for some reason is not
considered due recognition in Iran.

00:53:48.010 --> 00:53:52.130
Everybody talks about
Reborn and nobody talks

00:53:52.130 --> 00:53:57.190
about those three first poems
which are the pain of a woman

00:53:57.190 --> 00:54:00.990
who is trying to break
free from these molds

00:54:00.990 --> 00:54:03.730
that are imprisoning her.

00:54:03.730 --> 00:54:07.010
Again, it's not that she
didn't want to be a mother.

00:54:07.010 --> 00:54:10.810
She wanted to reconcile
it with being an artist.

00:54:10.810 --> 00:54:15.440
And that right was
not granted to her.

00:54:15.440 --> 00:54:17.600 position:56%
This is a picture of [Foreign name].

00:54:17.600 --> 00:54:23.380
So after the publication
of [Foreign name],

00:54:23.380 --> 00:54:29.070
Forough attempted another suicide.

00:54:29.070 --> 00:54:38.970
She was taken to psychiatric
hospital.

00:54:38.970 --> 00:54:43.920
She was hospitalized,
institutionalized for a month.

00:54:43.920 --> 00:54:46.670
She was given electric
shock therapy.

00:54:46.670 --> 00:54:52.020
And when she left, this is
a picture soon after it.

00:54:53.400 --> 00:54:55.840
She decided to leave Iran.

00:54:55.840 --> 00:54:58.410
She left Iran on a cargo plane.

00:54:58.410 --> 00:55:01.320
And in some of the
letters that you will read

00:55:01.320 --> 00:55:05.780
in the published letters you
see how she has to scramble

00:55:05.780 --> 00:55:09.490
to get the money to go to Europe.

00:55:09.490 --> 00:55:11.290
She wanted to study.

00:55:11.290 --> 00:55:14.970
She went to Italy and
then she went to Germany.

00:55:14.970 --> 00:55:17.300
She worked while she was in Italy.

00:55:17.300 --> 00:55:21.260
She did some dubbing,
she did some sewing.

00:55:21.260 --> 00:55:25.430
And after 16 months
she decided to return.

00:55:25.430 --> 00:55:31.010
She needed Iran and she needed
the language and the people.

00:55:31.010 --> 00:55:39.060
She went back to Iran and of course
not having high education it was

00:55:39.060 --> 00:55:40.910
hard to find a job.

00:55:40.910 --> 00:55:46.040
So she was introduced
to Galistan Film Studio.

00:55:46.040 --> 00:55:53.160
Mr. Galistan, a pioneer of Iranian
cinema and Iranian literature,

00:55:53.160 --> 00:55:59.540
hired her as a filing clerk.

00:55:59.540 --> 00:56:06.810
So she started her position there
to be economically independent

00:56:06.810 --> 00:56:09.520
and to finally have
a room of her own.

00:56:09.520 --> 00:56:19.340
She started working there, showing
afterward a very passionate,

00:56:19.340 --> 00:56:26.000
lustful, loving relationship
developed between the two.

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:32.440
And for the last eight
years of her life,

00:56:32.440 --> 00:56:38.100
Farrokhzhad had a very intense
relationship with Galistan.

00:56:38.100 --> 00:56:42.220
As you know, her fourth
poetry collection is dedicated

00:56:42.220 --> 00:56:44.260
to EG, Ebrahim Golistan.

00:56:44.260 --> 00:56:53.150
Some of the poems in [Foreign name]
I believe are the most beautiful

00:56:53.150 --> 00:56:58.750
poems a woman has ever
written about a man.

00:56:58.750 --> 00:57:02.410
I often tell Mr. Golistan I
think he's the prince charming

00:57:02.410 --> 00:57:03.830
of Persian literature.

00:57:03.830 --> 00:57:07.920
No man, to the best of my
knowledge, has been loved

00:57:07.920 --> 00:57:11.640
and adulated the way
Mr. Golistan has been

00:57:11.640 --> 00:57:15.560
in Persian literature
in Forough's poetry.

00:57:15.560 --> 00:57:20.100
Forough started travelling.

00:57:20.100 --> 00:57:26.220
Mr. Golistan recognized
that she is highly talented.

00:57:26.220 --> 00:57:29.700
She showed interest in film.

00:57:29.700 --> 00:57:38.690
And in 1962 she was
sent to a leprosarium.

00:57:38.690 --> 00:57:41.880
Bhabubhaki Leprosarium.

00:57:41.880 --> 00:57:49.570
In which she made the movie -- I
assume most of you have seen it.

00:57:49.570 --> 00:57:54.620
If not, please allow me to
recommend you watch that film.

00:57:54.620 --> 00:57:57.800
It's a 22-minute documentary.

00:57:57.800 --> 00:58:05.550
It has been considered by many
Iranian and western film critics

00:58:05.550 --> 00:58:09.610
as one of the best 10
documentaries made in the world.

00:58:09.610 --> 00:58:16.810
And this young woman in her
20's with minimal possibilities

00:58:16.810 --> 00:58:20.580
and resources made
this amazing movie.

00:58:20.580 --> 00:58:25.820
My introduction to Forough
Farrokhzhad was actually

00:58:25.820 --> 00:58:28.200
through that film.

00:58:28.200 --> 00:58:31.930
I vividly recall the first
time I saw that film.

00:58:31.930 --> 00:58:38.850
Images of disfigured
patients of leprosy.

00:58:38.850 --> 00:58:42.200
It was a summer day in Tehran.

00:58:42.200 --> 00:58:44.760
The smell of jasmine everywhere.

00:58:44.760 --> 00:58:50.170
I remember what I was
wearing, where I was sitting.

00:58:50.170 --> 00:58:54.750
Certainly I saw these images on
the screen of the television.

00:58:54.750 --> 00:59:00.360 position:56%
I could neither look at these
images nor could I take my eyes off.

00:59:00.360 --> 00:59:05.600
It was the most powerful
visual poetry I have ever seen.

00:59:05.600 --> 00:59:10.010
Since then, Forough
Farrokhzhad became my companion.

00:59:10.010 --> 00:59:15.860
Her poetry became my
garden, my home.

00:59:15.860 --> 00:59:23.790
Every time I go to
it, it's welcoming.

00:59:23.790 --> 00:59:26.080
I smell my childhood.

00:59:26.080 --> 00:59:29.850
I regain the lost time.

00:59:29.850 --> 00:59:35.950
It's beautiful poetry and it
has a special meaning for me.

00:59:35.950 --> 00:59:42.800
So I came to this country
in 1967, December of 1967.

00:59:42.800 --> 00:59:46.360
I wanted to do my dissertation.

00:59:46.360 --> 00:59:51.520 position:56%
My major was French literature and
I was going to write my dissertation

00:59:51.520 --> 00:59:57.900
on Flaubert and his search for the
ideal woman and the perfect words.

00:59:57.900 --> 01:00:01.790
My argument was that
neither will be possible

01:00:01.790 --> 01:00:07.100
because they don't exist unless
you change your perspective.

01:00:07.100 --> 01:00:15.120
But so thanks to Dr. Banani,
my teacher and my mentor,

01:00:15.120 --> 01:00:20.740 position:56%
I switched major again and I decided
to write my dissertation on Forough.

01:00:20.740 --> 01:00:25.730
But I was going to write my
dissertation on her biography.

01:00:25.730 --> 01:00:28.860
So that's in the '70's.

01:00:28.860 --> 01:00:32.590
I went to Iran repeatedly
for my research.

01:00:32.590 --> 01:00:37.210
And soon I realized that writing
her biography was impossible.

01:00:37.210 --> 01:00:45.120 position:56%
To give you quickly the reasons why,
many men were all too eager to share

01:00:45.120 --> 01:00:48.520
with me their love affair
with Forough Farrokhzhad.

01:00:48.520 --> 01:00:51.130
I was not interested in that.

01:00:51.130 --> 01:00:55.520
Those who knew the most will
tell me, what's the point

01:00:55.520 --> 01:00:58.200
of talking about a dead person?

01:00:58.200 --> 01:01:01.990
Many people made fun of me.

01:01:01.990 --> 01:01:08.010
So in America they give
a Ph. D for a woman

01:01:08.010 --> 01:01:12.980
who barely got her
high school diploma.

01:01:12.980 --> 01:01:15.570
And on and on.

01:01:15.570 --> 01:01:19.640
I have often told Mr. Golistan,
so I can tell you that.

01:01:19.640 --> 01:01:24.060
And when I finally met Mr.
Golistan and started asking him

01:01:24.060 --> 01:01:27.390
about Forough Farrokhzhad,
he looked at me.

01:01:27.390 --> 01:01:31.930
He said, "Miss Milani, I have
heard you are a good cook."

01:01:31.930 --> 01:01:36.870 position:56%
And I thought he was trying to
compliment me, the idiot that I was.

01:01:36.870 --> 01:01:40.360
And I said, "Who told you?"

01:01:40.360 --> 01:01:44.190
He said, "Your teacher Dr. Banani
tells me you are a good cook."

01:01:44.190 --> 01:01:46.670
And Mr. Banani was a chef.

01:01:46.670 --> 01:01:49.750
I said, "If he says it,
maybe I am not a bad cook."

01:01:49.750 --> 01:01:51.880
I was still clueless.

01:01:51.880 --> 01:01:54.390
He said, "I have a
suggestion for you.

01:01:54.390 --> 01:01:58.440
Why don't you write a cookbook?"

01:01:58.440 --> 01:02:04.260
So that was the end of my
biographical enterprise.

01:02:04.260 --> 01:02:08.980
But I promised myself I
will keep working at it.

01:02:08.980 --> 01:02:11.320
And I have for 37 years.

01:02:11.320 --> 01:02:17.360
It has been a while, but I
have finally almost done it.

01:02:17.360 --> 01:02:22.830
And I will quickly tell you
before I finish where I got

01:02:22.830 --> 01:02:26.590
after all these years of
agony and not knowing what

01:02:26.590 --> 01:02:30.020
to do, where I found my model.

01:02:30.020 --> 01:02:35.210
And how I'm trying
to do this biography.

01:02:37.110 --> 01:02:44.470
The film, The House is Black is
the biography of a leprosarium,

01:02:44.470 --> 01:02:46.700
at least that's how I see it.

01:02:46.700 --> 01:02:51.280
It's about life of
patients in a leprosarium,

01:02:51.280 --> 01:02:58.290 position:56%
a colony where lepers were
ostracized and literally imprisoned.

01:02:58.290 --> 01:03:07.200
The way she tells the truth, the
way she doesn't sugarcoat anything.

01:03:07.200 --> 01:03:13.070
The way she does not invade
privacy, the way she is devoted

01:03:13.070 --> 01:03:20.310
to imparting truth as she
saw it without judging,

01:03:20.310 --> 01:03:24.760
without moralizing,
was a lesson to me.

01:03:24.760 --> 01:03:27.830
This is a tall order
for any biographer.

01:03:27.830 --> 01:03:30.660
And I'm not sure I will succeed.

01:03:30.660 --> 01:03:36.720
But I can tell you with certainty
that it has been my model.

01:03:36.720 --> 01:03:42.970
You know, I would like to be
revealing but not voyeuristic.

01:03:42.970 --> 01:03:48.500
I would like to be
candid, but not judgmental.

01:03:48.500 --> 01:03:55.860
I would like to be informative
but respectful of someone

01:03:55.860 --> 01:04:01.390
who suffered all her life because
her privacy was not respected.

01:04:01.390 --> 01:04:06.140
So that's also the reason that
I have been sitting on some

01:04:06.140 --> 01:04:08.710
of these letters for decades.

01:04:08.710 --> 01:04:13.020
Because those letter were
not addressed to all of us.

01:04:13.020 --> 01:04:16.160
Those letters were
addressed to one person.

01:04:16.160 --> 01:04:20.780
And I was not sure, even though
the people that I have come

01:04:20.780 --> 01:04:24.770
into contact, the people I have
interviewed, were kind enough,

01:04:24.770 --> 01:04:28.820
generous enough to
give me those letters.

01:04:28.820 --> 01:04:32.430
And I knew I have to
share it with people,

01:04:32.430 --> 01:04:34.790
but I wasn't sure I'm invading.

01:04:34.790 --> 01:04:37.000
I'm not invading her privacy.

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:41.980
So finally after seeing that film,
and after seeing what she has done

01:04:41.980 --> 01:04:51.320
to leprosy, which is a disease that
we always covered up, I said, "No,

01:04:51.320 --> 01:04:54.480
she now belongs to
Iranian literature.

01:04:54.480 --> 01:04:56.850
She now belongs to Iran."

01:04:56.850 --> 01:05:02.310
And after 50 years, after
so many misinformation

01:05:02.310 --> 01:05:06.060
and so much information
and misinformation on her,

01:05:06.060 --> 01:05:09.190
we need to hear her own voice.

01:05:09.190 --> 01:05:14.540
So these are pictures of the son
she adopted at the leprosarium.

01:05:14.540 --> 01:05:20.460
She came back with this son
Hossein Mansouri and again she is

01:05:20.460 --> 01:05:27.250
to the best of my knowledge the
first woman who began this idea

01:05:27.250 --> 01:05:31.700
of single parenthood
and adopting a child.

01:05:31.700 --> 01:05:36.440
These are precious pictures that I
don't think you've ever seen before

01:05:36.440 --> 01:05:41.300
of Forough at the leprosarium.

01:05:41.300 --> 01:05:48.240
And finally just to give you an
idea of the published letters.

01:05:48.240 --> 01:05:51.690
Altogether Forough has published
a little less than 80 letters

01:05:51.690 --> 01:05:53.840
that have been published so far.

01:05:53.840 --> 01:05:58.300
Most of them were published,
56 letters.

01:05:58.300 --> 01:06:02.410
55 to Parviz Shapour
and one to his mother.

01:06:02.410 --> 01:06:07.090
So a total of 56 in a
collection [Foreign name],

01:06:07.090 --> 01:06:12.340
A Man the First Throb of My
Loving Heart, for her husband.

01:06:12.340 --> 01:06:17.690
It is a very interesting,
fascinating book.

01:06:17.690 --> 01:06:21.680
And just a few other short poems.

01:06:21.680 --> 01:06:27.140
All of these letters have
been censored in a way.

01:06:27.140 --> 01:06:31.790
There are words missing, a sentence
missing, a paragraph missing.

01:06:31.790 --> 01:06:34.630
I have chosen not to do that.

01:06:34.630 --> 01:06:39.270
Not a single word will be
deleted from the 30 letters.

01:06:39.270 --> 01:06:43.570
And I'm going to have her
own handwriting side-by-side

01:06:43.570 --> 01:06:50.050
with the transcribed version of it
so that you can read for yourself.

01:06:50.050 --> 01:06:58.030
As you see, the letters span
from her early teenage years

01:06:58.030 --> 01:07:06.180
to the last 15 letters she wrote
from Europe to Mr. Golistan.

01:07:06.180 --> 01:07:12.050
And I think they are very
important literary documents.

01:07:12.050 --> 01:07:15.510
Thank you very much for listening.

01:07:15.510 --> 01:07:18.090
[ Applause ]

